  "excerpt": "Need some inspiration for your DIY arts and crafts projects? Check out these free websites.",
  "siteName": "MakeUseOf",
  "favicon": "https://www.makeuseof.com/public/build/images/favicon-240x240.df310da5.png",
  "text": "Quick Links Sometimes, it's nice to take a little time away from our devices and do something different. But it's not always easy to find an activity interesting enough to keep us occupied for long enough. Why not give your creative side a chance with some DIY craft projects? 1 Happiness Is Homemade Happiness Is Homemade is a great resource that offers arts and crafts ideas to people of all ages. It includes seasonal ideas such as that for Thanksgiving, Christmas, or Halloween, and there are also a variety of projects you can occupy yourself with year-round. Simply click on Crafts + DIY to find the perfect project for you. This site doesn't just offer ideas but also printable pieces, such as coloring templates, stencils, and foldable 3D grids, which you can find in the Printables section. What's more, this section offers free printable games, like crosswords and bingo sheets, as well as free home decor graphics. There's also a wide range of SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) files on offer for those who want to grab some pre-designed stickers and labels for free. 2 Ravelry Ravelry is the best website when it comes to finding patterns for crocheting, knitting, and types of fiber arts. After creating an account, you can use the site's multiple filters to narrow down your search to free patterns. Some Raverly patterns have a free PDF that you can print if you'd prefer not to read off a screen. For example, if you're looking to knit a hat, you can use the filters to only show knitting patterns for hats. From there, you can even refine the search by the weight of the yarn, needle size you have on hand, and whether you want to make a child-size or adult-sized hat. You can click the heart icon to favorite patterns you want to return to later. Ravelry is a great website to look for inspiration if you have a big yarn stash or want to find things to make as gifts for holidays and birthdays! 3 Good Housekeeping You've probably heard of Good Housekeeping; it's a popular paper publication, but it also has its own website, where you can find some amazing DIY and creative ideas. Open the menu and navigate to Home Ideas \u003e Crafts \u0026 DIY Projects, and you'll have access to an array of arts and crafts inspiration for children and adults. In this section, you can learn how to stitch, get DIY crafts ideas for kids, and find gorgeous DIY homeware tutorials. On top of this, you can learn how to make sustainable kitchenware, such as beeswax wraps, and how to upcycle your old furniture or ornaments into gorgeous new pieces. You can even learn how to knit your own clothing! Good Housekeeping also offers decoration ideas, so you can plan how you're going to display your arts and crafts projects in your home. What's not to love about your very own DIY decor? 4 Ribblr Ribblr is similar to Ravelry in that it's a database of user-created patterns for different yarn projects. You can use the search bar and filters to only look at free patterns in knitting, crochet, or both techniques. There's an option to favorite patterns to return to later, and you can follow your favorite pattern creators on Ribblr to keep up with their latest projects. Ribblr frequently hosts pattern giveaways, offers free patterns during holiday countdowns, and lets you start a virtual journal to track your progress in any given project. The home page also shows trending patterns, and when you click on a pattern, there will be an array of similar patterns to check out. The one downside to Ribblr, however, is that you cannot access a printable PDF of a pattern because the platform is eco-friendly and trying to cut down on paper use. 5 Sarah Maker The Sarah Maker crafts website, founded by a DIY enthusiast, is a great resource for finding arts and crafts ideas as well as learning new skills. Here, you can learn how to make your own quilts, clay jewelry, tie-dye clothing, festive ornaments, friendship bracelets, face masks, and embroider gorgeous patterns and badges. There's a designated section for crochet, where you can learn how to crochet scarves, hats, blankets, and more. The step-by-step crochet tutorials for beginners are great for those who are new to this hobby. 6 All Free Crafts All Free Crafts has all sorts of crafts for every skill level. You can sort the crafts by holiday and skill level, too, if you're trying to create decorations for a holiday party. There are entire sections dedicated to recycling common household items like old denim, cardboard, and even lightbulbs! This website also features lots of nature and outdoor crafts for hobbies like bird watching. For example, there are crafts to create your own bird feeders and birdhouses. There are crafts for every kind of crafter on All Free Crafts. While there are sewing, knit, and crochet patterns, there are also others like a DIY scone jar, candles, paper crafts, and soaps. 7 Yarnspirations Yarnspirations is a great website that offers free patterns for crochet and knit projects. You can sort the projects from beginner to advanced based on your skill level. This website has all sorts of patterns, from blankets, to wearables like hats and skirts, to pillows and so much more. Yarnspirations partners with yarn brands like Red Heart and Caron, too, so you can purchase the yarn you need for a specific project directly from the website. It also provides yarn recommendations. There are also a ton of free resources with beginner guides on how to knit and crochet, helpful tips, and even other crafting activities like macramé and quilting on the site. It can be hard to come up with your own ideas for DIY projects, especially if you're not a seasoned arts and crafts enthusiast. But with the sites we've listed here, you'll have access to seemingly endless fun and creative DIY ideas, and for free too. Happy crafting!",
